  "output": "Confirmed scale: `sources.yaml` configures 114 ATS sources, several of which (Microsoft, Amazon, Netflix) paginate up to 30-40 pages of ~10 jobs each — so a full run can produce thousands of `Job` records flowing through `diff()` and `filter_jobs()`. That makes the two hot-path issues below real, not theoretical.\n\nNote: this is a pure Python pipeline (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), there's no React/frontend code in the repo, so I skipped that category.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job, `diff()` does one `SELECT` to check if it exists, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With 114 sources and boards like Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix producing hundreds-to-thousands of rows each, a full run means **thousands of individual round trips** to SQLite instead of a handful of batch statements.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    new, changed = [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    # one query for all existing hashes instead of one per job\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk\n        ).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    to_insert, to_update, to_touch = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append(row)\n        else:\n            to_touch.append({\"key\": job.key, \"now\": now})\n\n    if to_insert:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id,\n            title, url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at,\n            salary_range, content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n            :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url,\n            location=:location, department=:department,\n            employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if to_touch:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", to_touch)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns `O(N)` round trips into `O(N/900)` for the lookup plus 3 batched `executemany` calls.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside** the per-job loop (`filter_jobs` calls `match(j, ...)` once per job, and each call recompiles the same keyword list from scratch). For N jobs and M keywords that's `re.compile` invoked `N × M` times for identical patterns.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nCompile once outside the loop; `match()` now takes pre-compiled patterns.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-75` (`content_hash` hashed twice per job)\n\nIn `Store.diff`, `job.content_hash` is accessed directly for comparison, then `to_row()` (called by `_insert`/`_update`) calls `self.content_hash` again via `asdict()`. Since it's a plain `@property`, that's a full SHA-256 over the title/location/url/department blob computed **twice per job**. `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, so `functools.cached_property` won't work as-is (no `__dict__`) — add a dedicated slot:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str = field(default=\"\", repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if not self._content_hash:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\n(`to_row()`'s `asdict()` will now also emit `_content_hash` — pop it alongside `raw`.)\n\n## 4. Missed concurrency opportunity — `fetchers.py:422-470` (`fetch_workday`)\n\nWorkday pagination is sequential even though the API returns `total` after the very first request (`data.get(\"total\", ...)` — line 466). Every subsequent page is awaited one at a time instead of firing all remaining pages once the page count is known:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    ...\n    first = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\",\n                             json={\"appliedFacets\": {}, \"limit\": page_size,\n                                   \"offset\": 0, \"searchText\": \"\"},\n                             headers={\"Accept\": \"application/json\"})\n    postings = first.get(\"jobPostings\", []) if isinstance(first, dict) else []\n    total = min(first.get(\"total\", len(postings)), 5000)\n    jobs = [_to_job(company, host, locale, site, p) for p in postings]\n\n    offsets = range(page_size, total, page_size)\n    async def fetch_page(offset):\n        body = {\"appliedFacets\": {}, \"limit\": page_size, \"offset\": offset, \"searchText\": \"\"}\n        data = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json=body,\n                                headers={\"Accept\": \"application/json\"})\n        return data.get(\"jobPostings\", []) if isinstance(data, dict) else []\n\n    pages = await asyncio.gather(*(fetch_page(o) for o in offsets))\n    for postings in pages:\n        jobs.extend(_to_job(company, host, locale, site, p) for p in postings)\n    return jobs\n```\n\nNote the existing outer semaphore (`fetch_all`, concurrency=8) already caps global concurrency, so this doesn't risk a thundering herd against Workday — it just replaces per-source serial waiting with parallel waiting.\n\n## Not applicable / lower priority\n- **Memory leaks**: none found — this is a short-lived CLI process (`cli.py` → `run_sync` → exit), so nothing outlives the run. `Job.raw` does hold full per-posting JSON in memory for the whole pipeline (fetch → filter → diff) before being dropped in `to_row()`, which raises peak memory on large multi-source runs, but it's bounded and reclaimed at process exit — not worth optimizing unless you hit real memory pressure.\n- **React re-renders**: not applicable — no frontend in this repo.\n- **Caching**: `Job.posted_dt` (models.py:60-63) re-parses the timestamp string on every access via `parse_posted_at`, but it's currently only read once per job in `filters.match()`, so caching wouldn't pay off unless a future caller reads it multiple times.\n\nWant me to apply fixes #1 and #2 (the two with clear, immediate wins at your current 114-source scale)?\n",
